feminist history. Provocations includes engaging, historically significant primary sources by writers of many nationalities in numerous genres—from political manifestos to theoretical and cultural analysis to poetry and fiction. These texts range from those of classical antiquity to others composed during the Arab Spring and represent Asia, the Middle East, Latin America, Western Europe, and the United States. Each section begins with an introductory essay that presents central ideas and explores connections among readings, placing them in historical, national, and intellectual contexts and concluding with questions for discussion and reflection.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismxHistory. 4aHistory. 4aWomen. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh1 aAbney, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Ali, Nadje, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlcalde, M. Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlcalde, M. Cristina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAllen, Paula Gunn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarton, Bernadette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasu, Srimati, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeauboeuf-Lafontant, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackwell, Maylei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBordo, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBordo, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBourgeois, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurrill, Emily, econtributor.4ctb